        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Bromley Kent</placeName>
                    <date>Dec. 2<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>—</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I cannot remember whether I acknowledged your last note— — Anyhow I hope to meet you on the 10<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>,<ref target="#foot.f1"/> as near as I can arrive by 1 o’clock at Woods’ Hotel Furnival Inn.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Your’s very faithfully | C. Darwin</p>
<p>P.S. | I have just received your note, enclosing your account, &amp; I have received information from the Union Bank, that they have placed to my account from you <hi rend="superscript">£</hi>225 : 6<hi rend="superscript">s</hi> : 5<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>, for which I am much obliged.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/> <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/> Dec. 3<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>.</p>
<p>C. Darwin</p>
<p>P.S. When we meet you must tell me, whether you w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. prefer <formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></formula> yearly a receipt on a stamp now that the stamp-laws are altered<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">There is an entry recording a visit to London on that day in CD’s Account book (Down House MS).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Furnival’s Inn, Holborn, London (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6380.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Post Office London directory</hi></ref> 1853).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD recorded the receipt of £225 11<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 5<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. on 3 December 1853 in his Classed account book (Down House MS) for the rent from Beesby farm.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">Among the wide-ranging changes in taxes and duties put forward by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1883.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Ewart Gladstone</ref> in the budget of 1853, was the introduction of a penny duty to be charged on documents functioning as receipts. After the new measure came into force on 11 October 1853, any receipt for a sum of £2 or more had to carry a one penny stamp if it was to be an admissible record of the transaction (<hi rend="italic">Annual Register</hi> (1853): 56; <hi rend="italic">Economist</hi> 11 (1853): 1127). CD’s next surviving <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1615.xml" resp="#automat" cert="medium">letter to Higgins acknowledging the receipt of rent, of 25 December 1854</ref>, bears the appropriate stamp.</note>
        </div>        
            
